title: Severance S2E1 ‘Hello, Ms. Cobel’ (2025)
description: In the Severance Season 2 premiere, "Hello, Ms. Cobel," Mark S. awakens on the severed floor and discovers that five months have passed since the innies' revolt, with Mr. Milchick now managing the floor and new employees in the Macrodata Refinement department. As Mark grapples with these changes, he reunites with Helly, Dylan, and Irving, and they confront the implications of their uprising and the evolving dynamics within Lumon Industries.

description: The visually striking "Humble" music video, directed by Dave Meyer and reminiscent of Hype Williams' style, breathes life into Kendrick Lamar's ideas, setting the tone for his upcoming album, which appears to focus on his status as a superstar rather than a complex concept.

title: Audrey Nuna - Cellulite (2023)
description: Audrey Nuna's "Cellulite" music video, directed by Zac Dov, is a vivid narrative of self-liberation and defiance, drawing inspiration from icons like the Pharcyde and Missy Elliott. The video visually represents Nuna's personal theme of overcoming constraints, symbolized by motifs of flying and motion, reflecting her introspective yet rebellious spirit. It's a cinematic portrayal of cutting out life's "toxic fat," aiming to resonate with viewers on a journey of spiritual unburdening.

title: Victoria Monet - Alright (2024)
description: The music video for "Alright" by Victoria Monét, directed by Dave Meyers, is a vibrant homage to Janet Jackson, featuring high-energy choreography and striking visuals. In the video, Monét channels Jackson's iconic style, wearing a black-and-white fedora and suit, and performing dynamic dance routines reminiscent of Jackson's 1990s and 2000s era. The video, choreographed by Sean Bankhead, showcases Monét's impressive dance skills and captures the essence of liberation and celebration. Made in collaboration with Jacobi Mehringer, Anna Arnell, and Mia Barnes.

title: Kyan Khojandi - Haagen-Dazs (2021)
description: Slow bolt arm shot in void environment. The BOLT was popularized in Dave Meyer's 'Humble' where it quickly moved around Kendrick. In this clip, we see it's use at a more normal speed.
